# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-chinese-milk-scandal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] 'October 25 Opposing Evil Minds and Looking out for Taiwan March') was a demonstration on 25 October 2008 sponsored by the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) and Taiwan Solidarity Union in Taipei, Taiwan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] This protest march was launched five months after the inauguration of President Ma Ying-jeou and was preceded by an earlier 30 August 2008 protest in August which focused on Ma's failing economic plans.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The protesters marched against the perceived pro-China policies of the Ma administration.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] An estimated half a million people were reported to have participated in the march.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] It was planned by the DPP in response to the Chinese tainted milk powder scandal and Taiwan's perceived growing ties with the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The People's Republic of China claims that self-ruled Taiwan is its 23rd province.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The PRC has threatened the use of force if Taiwan declares *de jure* independence from China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Zhang Mingqing, the deputy chairman of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait, arrived in Taiwan about a week before the protest.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] When asked by reporters to comment on President Ma's remarks that there will be no war across the Taiwan Strait in the next four years, Zhang expressed that there will never be war in the Strait if there is no Taiwan independence.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] During a private visit to the Taiwan Confucian Temple in Tainan, Zhang fell to the ground as he encounters a small number of protesters led by the DPP's Tainan City legislator Wang Ting-yu.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] It was not clear whether he tripped or was pushed down, but Zhang was hurt.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The car that Zhang was in was attacked and damaged when a protester jumped on the top of the car.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Later, Zhang remarked, "Those who commit violence do not get what they want, but instead drop a rock on their own feet." as well as "A handful of compatriots in Tainan were involved in the violence (against me).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The safety of Chinese food products has become a major issue in Taiwan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The Ma administration's policy of normalising cross-strait relations has been perceived by the pro-independence supporters as forming closer ties with the PRC.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The milk scandal became not only a public health issue, but a political one as well.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The government's ability to address the issue was questioned by the general public and the media.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The Department of Health was heavily criticized by the Consumers' Foundation and investigated by the Control Yuan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Other than condemning the PRC, DPP demanded that President Ma should request compensation from the PRC.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] DPP chairwoman Tsai Ing-wen also criticized the government for being "weak" toward the PRC.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Some Kuomintang legislators, on the other hand, criticized the PRC government for notifying Taiwan late after the news had already been reported by Taiwanese media.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The planned starting point of the first route "Oppose Toxic Goods" was the Dinghao Plaza.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Some of the politicians who took this route were former President Chen Shui-bian, former president of the World United Formosans for Independence Peng Ming-min and current president Ng Chiau-tong, and former foreign minister Chen Tang-shan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The participants of the "Oppose One China Education" route started out in front of the main gate of the National Taiwan University.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Protesters are mostly students who resisted the government's policy to recognize mainland Chinese academic qualifications.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Leaders of this group include DPP chairwoman Tsai Ing-wen, former Kaohsiung mayor Yeh Chu-lan, current mayor Chen Chu, and Kaohsiung County magistrate Yang Chiu-hsing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The third route was organized by the TSU.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Protesters marched from the Lungshan Temple.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The TSU convened about 20,000 people including members of Victims of Investment in China Association.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The participants protested against Ma's perceived policy of "damaging Taiwan's sovereignty".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The fourth route was led by former premier Yu Shyi-kun, who was accompanied by Yunlin County magistrate Su Chih-fen, deputy magistrate Lee Ying-yuan, Tainan County magistrate Su Huan-chih, and Tainan mayor Hsu Tain-tsair.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Protesters held a banner with slogan "Love Yunlin, Rebut Chen Yunlin!" The last route "Oppose the Incompetent Government" was led by former DPP chairman Su Tseng-chang.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Because the protest march was launched primarily by the Democratic Progressive Party, participants were predominantly pan-green.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Former DPP chairmen Yao Chia-wen, Su Tseng-chang, and Yu Shyi-kun all participated in the march.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] Despite recent corruption controversies, former President Chen Shui-bian also marched and took the "Oppose Toxic Goods" route, although he did not finish the route.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] This was Chen's last appearance at a public political event before his arrest on November 11.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The DPP organizers announced that there were over 600,000 protesters.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] According to the pro-independence Taiwan East Society (Chinese: 台灣東社), there were some pan-blue or Kuomintang supporters who signed up for the event.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The chairman of the organization said that President Ma's pro-China policies had irritated many Taitung residents.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] When protesters asked a police officer whether her boss is President Ma or not, the officer, surnamed Chou, responded that she worked for the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The response irritated pan-green supporters, and an apology was immediately demanded.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] The director of the National Police Agency Wang Cho-chiun later publicly apologized for the conduct of the officer, saying she has "damaged the police's public image." Wang also said that the officer will be punished for sure.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1025-demonstration] President Ma Ying-jeou said he would listen to the voice of the people and respond to their criticism, but maintained that the main direction of his government policies remained the correct one.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In 1858 a batch of sweets in Bradford, England, was accidentally adulterated with poisonous arsenic trioxide.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] About five pounds (two kilograms) of sweets were sold to the public, leading to around 20 deaths and over 200 people suffering the effects of arsenic poisoning.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The adulteration of food had been practised in Britain since before the Middle Ages, but in the nineteenth century, with increasing urbanisation and the rise in shop-purchased food, adulterants became a growing problem.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] With the cost of sugar high, replacing it with substitutes was common.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] For the sweets produced in Bradford, the confectioner was supposed to purchase powdered gypsum, but a mistake at the wholesale chemist meant arsenic was purchased instead.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Three men were arrested—the chemist who sold the arsenic, his assistant and the sweet maker—but all three were acquitted after the judge decided it was all accidental and there was no case for any of them to answer.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths led to the Adulteration of Food or Drink Act 1860, although the legislation was criticised for being too ambiguous and the penalties for breaching it too low to act as a deterrent.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths were also a factor in the passage of the Pharmacy Act 1868.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Cost was the reason adulterants were used; sugar, for example, cost 6½d per pound; the adulterant cost ½d per pound.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The adulteration fell into three categories: firstly were harmless additions, such as chicory in coffee, adding flour to mustard and watering down milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] More serious were the addition of indigestible ingredients, including introducing alum, gypsum or chalk into white bread or tree or shrub leaves into tea leaves.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Finally, dangerous additions to foods included salts of copper and red lead glaze used as colourants, mercury salts added to cheese, and the use of arsenic, sulphuric acid and nitric acid.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The chemist Arthur Hill Hassall was prominent in the field of food analysis as an analytical microscopist who established levels of adulteration.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Between 1850 and 1856 he examined 3,000 samples of food and found 65 per cent of them contained adulterants.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Those involved in adulterating foodstuff used nicknames to hide the practice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] These included "daff", "duck", "duff", "derby", "multum", "flash" and "stuff".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] One local name used in Bradford—an industrial town in the West Riding of Yorkshire—was "daft".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In the Victorian era, arsenic was an ingredient in several household products, including medicines (for external and internal use), candles, wallpaper, soft furnishings and colourants for foods.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It was also used as a poison for murder.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] So many people died of arsenic poisoning—both deliberate and accidental—that legislation in the form of the Arsenic Act 1851 was introduced; it was the first piece of UK legislation to attempt to control the sale of a poisonous substance.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It stated that arsenic should only be sold to adults, the sale recorded in a book—signed by both seller and buyer—and that there should be a witness to the sale if the buyer was unknown to the seller.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Any arsenic not to be used for medicinal purposes was to be coloured with soot or indigo to differentiate it from other white powders on sale.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] There was no restriction on who could sell arsenic; no licence was required and any trader was able to sell it as long as they kept a record of the sale.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Although the act controlled the method of sale, it did not bring an end to arsenic-related problems or the widespread use of arsenic in household goods.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Arsenic trioxide—also known as white arsenic—is an industrially produced inorganic compound with the formula As 2O 3.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It is white and is commonly found in either powdered or crystal form—the latter resembling sugar or sand.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It is used as a wood preservative and a pesticide.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] As a solid it is tasteless, but when in solution, it is described as "very faint, at first sweetish, afterward very slightly metallic".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] William Hardaker, known to locals as "Humbug Billy", sold sweets from a stall in the Greenmarket in central Bradford.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hardaker purchased his confectionery from Joseph Neal, who made the sweets in Stone Street a few hundred yards to the north.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The sweets were peppermint lozenges, made by mixing peppermint oil into a base of sugar, water and gum, which was made into a paste, then dried on boards before being cut into lozenge shapes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] As the sugar was relatively expensive, Neal would substitute some of the sugar with powdered gypsum; he later justified his actions by saying "where I use a pound of it, there are people who will use a ton of it".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In the week before the regular Saturday market, Neal was due to make a batch of lozenges for Hardaker but had run out of "daft".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal asked his lodger, James Archer, to visit a druggist in the town of Shipley, five miles (eight kilometres) by road, to purchase the gypsum.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The druggist, Charles Hodgson, was ill in bed; his assistant, William Goddard, was on duty and had been told the daft was in a barrel in the attic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard had only been working for Hodgson for a few weeks, hoping for an apprenticeship.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Archer asked for the daft, Goddard went to the attic and took twelve pounds (five kilograms) of powder from a cask.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard did not realise that there were two identical barrels and he had taken powder from a barrel of arsenic trioxide; the barrel was only labelled as such on the base.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal employed James Appleton—an experienced sweetmaker—to manufacture the lozenges.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Both men thought the new batch of sweets was different from normal: Appleton thought the mixture was more free-flowing and smoother than normal, and both considered the end product was a darker shade than they were used to.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Appleton, working closely with the arsenic, fell ill and suffered from fits of vomiting; Neal, who occasionally tasted the lozenges to check the quality, also began vomiting.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neither man connected their sickness to the lozenges.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Hardaker collected the sweets from Neal on 30 October 1858 he also noted the different colour from the normal batches.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He negotiated the lower price of 7+1⁄2d per pound for forty pounds (eighteen kilograms), a discount of 1⁄2d per pound on his usual price.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hardaker sold the sweets for two ounces (fifty-seven grams) for 1+1⁄2d.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He ate some of the sweets and by 5:30 pm he became ill; he went home and left his assistant to look after the stall until it closed at 11:30 pm, by which point about a thousand sweets had been sold.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] On the Sunday morning the local police were informed of the deaths of a man named Elijah Wright and two boys, aged 9 and 14, the sons of John Scott; it was thought that the cause of the deaths was cholera.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The misdiagnosis of cholera instead of arsenic poisoning was a common mistake, as the symptoms for both—vomiting, abdominal pain and diarrhoea—were similar and England was affected by an ongoing cholera pandemic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When more deaths were reported during the course of Sunday, Police Constable Campbell was sent to investigate; he made the connection between the sweets and the deaths, and visited Hardaker, seizing the remaining stock, which was just under thirty-six pounds (sixteen kilograms).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Campbell then went to Neal's premises and seized six ounces (one hundred and seventy grams) of fragments of the sweets.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] A detective, William Burniston, went to Shipley with Archer to visit Hodgson, the druggist.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Archer indicated the cask from which the powder had been dispensed, Hodgson immediately identified it as containing arsenic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Burniston arrested Goddard, the assistant.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The chief constable, William Leveratt, had been kept abreast of developments, and deployed men to local inns and alehouses to spread warnings about the lozenges.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He sent out bellmen to announce the warnings across the town and, at 11 pm, he had warning notices printed up and posted overnight for people to see in the morning.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] A local doctor, John Henry Bell, hypothesised the poisonings of his patients were caused by arsenic; he gave the lozenges from one patient to an analytical chemist, who confirmed his theory.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Bell treated sixty patients for the poisoning.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] By midday on the Monday—1 November—the number of dead had risen to twelve, with seventy-eight people seriously ill.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Police visited Neal for a second time and searched his premises more thoroughly, finding hundreds of fragments still on the drying boards used when preparing the lozenges.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal's wife also admitted that she had found other fragments and thrown them onto the fire; she had also been to their own sweetshop and brought back some bags of mixed sweets that contained lozenges or lozenge fragments.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] While the police were there, Neal ran off and was pursued; he was found sitting in his kitchen at home.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard was brought in front of the magistrates on the Monday; he was remanded in custody.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] An inquest was opened the following day.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The magistrates also met and decided that Hodgson should also be arrested and remanded.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] On Wednesday the magistrates also decided that Neal should also be arrested, although he was released on bail.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] They heard from an analytical chemist, Felix Rimmington, who estimated that each sweet contained nine grains (580 mg) of arsenic; he added that four and a half grains were sufficient to kill an adult male.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Rimmington later made an analysis of the lozenges which showed each contained between eleven and sixteen grains (710 and 1,040 mg).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] By the end of Wednesday, fifteen people had been reported dead, eleven of whom were children; thirteen more were listed as "dangerously ill", and another hundred and fifty were ill but not in danger.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The magistrates met again on the Friday and determined that the three men in custody should be sent to the next York assizes for trial on a charge of manslaughter by negligence.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Bail for Hodgson and Neal was set at £200; that for Goddard was set at £100.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The number of dead had risen to seventeen, with 196 people ill.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Eventually up to twenty-one people died and over two hundred were sick; figures on the number of deaths vary, with either twenty or twenty-one people dead.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The assizes opened on 9 December 1858; the judge was Mr Baron Warren.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In his opening remarks he said that there was no case for Neal to answer as he was not present when the arsenic was purchased or when the lozenges were made, and dismissed the case against him.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard, Warren said, was only following the instructions of his master and so also had no case to answer; his case was also dismissed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Warren said the case against Hodgson should stand and that he would be tried later in the month.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hodgson's trial opened on 21 December 1858 for the manslaughter of Elizabeth Mary Midgley, a seven-year-old girl.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] If he was found guilty of the charge, others would follow.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] After hearing some of the evidence, the judge stopped the proceedings and said there was no case for Hodgson to answer; he instructed the jury to record a verdict of not guilty, which they did.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths led to calls for legislation to stop similar events occurring, and the Adulteration of Food or Drink Act 1860 was passed into law, "on a wave of public revulsion" against the event at Bradford, according to the microbiologist John Postgate.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] According to the legal scholar Jillian London, "Although the Bradford incident was far from solely responsible for the passage of the 1860 Act, it was instrumental in heightening public awareness of and outrage towards adulteration".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The political economist Sébastien Rioux observes that the law only applied when adulterated food was being passed off as pure, so the protection was only on misrepresenting what was being sold, rather than ensuring the purity of all food.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Whorton considers the Act "was next to useless" as its provisions were too ambiguous and the penalties for breaching it—at £5—were too low to act as a deterrent.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The events at Bradford were still felt ten years later when the Pharmacy Act 1868 was passed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Legislation on pharmacies was considered from 1859 onwards, although the Royal Pharmaceutical Society opposed a Poison Bill in 1859.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In 1900, more than 6,000 people in England were poisoned by arsenic-tainted beer, with more than 70 of the affected dying as a result.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The food safety crisis was caused by arsenic entering the supply chain through impure sugar which had been made with contaminated sulphuric acid.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The illness was prevalent across the Midlands and North West England, with Manchester being the most heavily affected.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Originally misdiagnosed as alcoholic neuropathy, the main epidemic was only recognised after several months.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Additionally, investigation into the outbreak found other sources of arsenic in beer, which had been unknowingly poisoning thousands in decades preceding the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This mass poisoning is unusual in that it was not noticed for four months.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The doctors, seeing patients who were usually heavy drinkers and who showed muscle weakness and numbness of the hands or feet, initially thought that the patients had "alcoholic neuritis".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nevertheless, a marked increase in the number of cases was noted, with 41 people succumbing to peripheral neuritis, multiple neuritis or alcoholic neuritis and 66 people perishing from alcoholism in the four months of the outbreak, while the previous seven months revealed only 22.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] These cases of neuritis were eventually connected to cases of skin discolouration previously thought to be unrelated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Ernest Reynolds, the doctor responsible for making the connection, also noted that only one substance would cause these symptoms: arsenic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] He also noted that heavy drinkers who drank mainly spirits seemed less affected than beer drinkers.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] He gathered samples for analysis from the taverns frequented by his patients, which confirmed the presence of arsenic in the beer they consumed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Once the breweries affected were identified, investigation as to where the arsenic came from were instituted.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] It was found that the arsenic was present in invert sugar provided to the breweries by Bostock & Co. of Garston.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] To lower costs in the tight-margin English beer market, some breweries substituted high-quality barley malt with low-quality barley malt supplemented with sugar.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This practice was somewhat controversial; as part of the Pure Beer movement, an inquiry on the use of brewing substitutes had been called.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This inquiry, starting in 1896 and ending in 1899, had concluded that brewing substitutes were not "deleterious materials" under the Sale of Food and Drugs Act 1875 (38 & 39 Vict. c.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] 63) and that further legislation was not required.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This sugar was made by acid hydrolysis of starch, where starch is heated in the presence of an acid to form glucose.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Such a method was not new, and had been employed commercially since at least 1814.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Bostock & Co. used sulphuric acid to perform the acid hydrolysis.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This acid, purchased from Nicholson & Sons, was made from pyrites which contained arsenic, which remained in the final product.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] John Nicholson & Sons, of Leeds, had provided sulphuric acid to Bostock & Co. since 1888.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] For most of the length of the business relationship, the acid provided was free from arsenic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] However, in March 1900, Nicholson started supplying unpurified sulphuric acid containing arsenic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This practice continued until November 1900, when the acid was found to be the cause of the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nicholson claimed that they did not know the nature of Bostock's use of the acid, and that they could have provided arsenic-free acid if requested.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Once the main source of the outbreak had been identified as arsenic poisoning, further investigation into arsenic contamination of beer was undertaken.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Eventually, it was found that arsenic was also introduced into beer by the malted barley.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In the kilning stage of malting, the barley humidity content is reduced by drying the grain with the hot vapours of a fire, usually fuelled by coke or coal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] It was found that when arsenic is present in the fuel, it could then be deposited upon the barley before steeping, and therefore would be present in the final product.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Investigation into the outbreak uncovered that most cases of alcoholic neuropathy endemic to Manchester were, in fact, misdiagnosed arsenic poisoning, with this alternative route being responsible for the poisoning of thousands in the years preceding the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Such contamination was tied to an outbreak in the borough of Halifax in January and February 1902 where 13 to 14 cases of arsenic poisoning were noted, three deadly.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The malt was dried over a non-sequestered gas coke fire, thus resulting in contaminated beer.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] After the cause of the poisoning was reported by the media, a considerable reduction in beer consumption was noted in the region.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The response from the brewing industry was mixed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] There was a strong, immediate reaction from some breweries, led by the large Manchester brewery Groves and Whitnall, who went as far as sending out telegrams to all the taverns and inns that had purchased their beer.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Breweries disposed of thousands of barrels of beer by dumping them in the city's sewers.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Other breweries were slower to respond, with fines being handed out to breweries whose beer samples could still be purchased by investigators.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Additionally, one pub was fined for selling contaminated beer after they were notified of the presence of arsenic by the manufacturer.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In Lancashire, 23 taverns and pubs were prosecuted for violations under section 6 of the Sale of Food and Drugs Act 1875.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Bostock & Co. went into liquidation, and sued Nicholson & Sons for damages, for breach of an implied condition under the Sale of Goods Act 1893.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nicholson & Sons survived, and was later acquired by B.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The poisoning resulted in the appointment of a Royal Commission led by Lord Kelvin, which submitted a preliminary report in 1901 and a final report in 1903.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The effects on the beer market were short-lived, and consumption of beer resumed over the course of the year.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Attempts to revive the pure beer movement were nullified by the commission's report, and by the fact that arsenic was present in malted barley as well as sugar.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] There seemed to be no direct effects on legislation resulting from the incident.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In 1901, a considerable decline in the birth rate was noted in Manchester, Salford and Liverpool.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This decline was greater in areas most affected, leading the Royal Commission to conclude that the epidemic was the cause.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1900-english-beer-poisoning] A 2026 study found, "the arsenic-in-beer epidemic caused a 10% drop in births in 1901, but the effect was short-lived.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The **1971 Iraq poison grain disaster** was a mass methylmercury poisoning incident where seed grain treated with a methylmercury fungicide, which was never intended for human consumption, was imported into Iraq from Mexico and the United States.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Due to factors like foreign-language labeling and distribution too late into the growing cycle, this toxic grain was consumed as food by Iraqi residents in rural areas of the country.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Sufferers experienced paresthesia (numbness of skin), ataxia (lack of coordination of muscle movements) and vision loss, symptoms similar to those observed in Minamata disease-affected Japan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Though the official death toll was 459, figures of as much as ten times greater have been suggested.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] When it occurred in 1971, the poisoning was the largest mercury poisoning event in history, with cases peaking in February 1972 and stopping by the end of March.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Reports after the disaster recommended tighter regulation, better labelling and handling of mercury-treated grain, and wider involvement of the World Health Organization in monitoring and preventing poisoning incidents.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Investigation confirmed the particular danger posed to fetuses and young children.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The properties of mercury make it an effective fungicide.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Methylmercury had been banned in Sweden in 1966, the first country to do so, and the United Kingdom followed in 1971.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Previous mercury-poisoning incidents had occurred in Iraq in 1956 and 1960.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1956, there had been around 200 cases, and 70 deaths; in 1960 there had been 1000 cases and 200 deaths, in both cases due to ethylmercury compounds.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Among the recommendations made after the 1960 incident had been to colour any toxic grain for easy identification.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Before the 1971 incident, around 200–300 cases of methylmercury poisoning had been reported worldwide.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Drought had reduced harvests in 1969, affecting 500,000 people, and in 1970.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some 95,000 tonnes (93,000 long tons; 105,000 short tons) of grain (73,202 tonnes of wheat grain and 22,262 tonnes of barley), coloured a pink-orange hue, were shipped to Iraq from the United States and Mexico.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The wheat arrived in Basra on SS *Trade Carrier* between 16 September and 15 October, the barley between 22 October and 24 November 1971.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Iraq's government chose Mexipak, a high-yield wheat seed developed in Mexico by Norman Borlaug.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The seeds contained an average of 7.9 μg/g of mercury, with some samples containing up to nearly twice that.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The three northern governorates of Nineveh, Kirkuk and Erbil received more than half the shipments.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Contributing factors to the epidemic included the fact that distribution started late, and much grain arrived after the October–November planting season.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers were supposed to plant the poisoned grain, but many instead offered it to their families as food, since their own planting had been completed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Distribution was, in later stages hurried and open, with grain being distributed free of charge with the expectation of payment in kind when the harvest season came.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some farmers even sold off their own grain, in order to claim more of the imported grain.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This left them dependent on tainted grain for the winter.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many Iraqis were either unaware of the significant health risk posed, or chose to ignore the warnings.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Initially, farmers were to certify with a thumbprint or signature that they understood the grain was poison, however some distributors ignored this requirement.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Warnings on the sacks were in Spanish and English, not at all understood, or included the black-and-white skull and crossbones design, which meant nothing to Iraqis.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The long, asymptomatic latent period of mercury poisoning may have granted farmers a false sense of security when animals fed the grain initially appeared to be fine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The red dye washed off the grain; the mercury did not.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Hence, washing may have given only the appearance of removing the poison.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi government made limited attempts to control the distribution of the mercury grain.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Four high ranking officials were posted at the Basra docks during the first two weeks of unloading.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] However, control of the unloading process slipped afterwards, with some spilt grain being stolen by dockworkers.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Aircraft were used to drop half a million leaflets warning of the mercury, however this was an insufficient quantity for the population at the time.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ground seed dust inhalation was a contributing factor in farmers during sowing and grinding.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Consumption of ground grain in homemade bread is thought to have been the major source of toxicity, since no cases were reported in urban areas, where government flour supplies were commercially regulated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The effect of mercury took some time – the latent period between ingestion and the first symptoms (typically paresthesia – numbness in the extremities) was between 16 and 38 days.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Paresthesia was the predominant symptom in less serious cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Worse cases included ataxia (typically loss of balance), blindness or reduced vision, and death resulting from central nervous system failure.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Anywhere between 20 and 40 mg of mercury has been suggested as sufficient for paresthesia (between 0.5 and 0.8 mg/kg of body weight).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] On average, individuals affected consumed 20 kg or so of bread; the 73,000 tonnes provided would have been sufficient for over 3 million cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The hospital in Kirkuk received large numbers of patients with symptoms that doctors recognised from the 1960 outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The first case of alkylmercury poisoning was admitted to hospital on 21 December.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By 26 December, the hospital had issued a specific warning to the government.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By January 1972, the government had started to strongly warn the populace against eating the grain, although dispatches did not mention the large numbers already ill.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi Army soon ordered disposal of the grain and eventually declared anyone found selling it would receive the death penalty.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers dumped their supplies wherever possible, contaminating the water supply (particularly the Tigris).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The government initiated a news blackout and released little information about the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The World Health Organization assisted the Iraqi government through the supply of drugs, analytical equipment and expertise.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many new treatments were tried, since existing methods for heavy metal poisoning were not particularly effective.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dimercaprol was administered to several patients, but caused rapid deterioration of their condition.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It was ruled out as a treatment for this sort of poisoning following the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Polythiol resins, penicillamine and dimercaprol sulfonate all helped, but are believed to have been largely insignificant in overall recovery and outcomes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dialysis was tested on a few patients late in the treatment period, but they showed no clinical improvement.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The result of all treatments was varied, with some patients' blood mercury level being dramatically reduced, but a negligible effect in others.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] All patients received periods of treatment interspersed with lay periods; continuous treatment was suggested in future cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Later treatment was less effective in reducing blood toxicity.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] 6,530 patients were admitted to hospitals with poisoning, and 459 deaths were reported.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Cases reached a peak of hundreds per day in January, and had largely subsided by the beginning of March.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Admissions represented every age and gender stratum, although those under the age of ten represented a third of admitted cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This number is "certainly an underestimate", because of the availability of hospital treatment, hospital overcrowding and lack of faith in treatment.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In the most severely affected areas, prevalence was 28% and mortality was 21% of the cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some Iraqi doctors believe both the number of cases and fatalities are at least ten times too low, with perhaps 100,000 cases of brain damage.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] One suggested reason for the vast discrepancy between reported and estimated numbers of deaths is the Iraqi custom, common to large parts of the Middle East, for a person to die at home when possible.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Home deaths would not have been recorded.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] A large number of patients with minor symptoms recovered completely; those with more serious symptoms improved.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This was in contrast to expected outcomes, largely based on analysis of Minamata disease in Japan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In boys with mercury levels below clinical poisoning, a reduction in school performance was noted, although this correlation could not be confirmed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In infants, the mercury poisoning caused central nervous system damage.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Relatively low doses caused slower development in children, and abnormal reflexes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Different treatments for mercury poisoning have since been developed, and "quiet baby syndrome", characterised by a baby who never cries, is now a recognised symptom of methylmercury-induced brain damage.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ongoing recommendations of the food regulation authorities have focused on consumption by pregnant women and infant children, noting the particular susceptibility of fetuses and infants to methylmercury poisoning.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Data from Iraq have confirmed that methylmercury can pass to a child *in utero*, and mercury levels were equal to or higher in the newborn child than in the mother.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1974, a joint Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and World Health Organization (WHO) meeting made several recommendations to prevent a similar outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] These included stressing the importance of labelling bags in the local language and with locally understood warning symbols.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The possibility of an additive creating a strong bitter taste was studied.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The meeting urged governments to strictly regulate methyl- and ethylmercury use in their respective countries, including limiting use to where no other reasonable alternative was available.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also recommended the involvement of the FAO and WHO in assisting national governments in regulation and enforcement, and the setting up of national poison control centres.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Over 9–13 November, a Conference on Intoxication due to Alkylmercury-Treated Seed was held in Baghdad.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It supported the recommendations of the FAO/WHO report and suggested that local and national media should publicise outbreaks, including size and symptoms; it considered the distribution of this information crucial.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also laid out a general plan as to the collection of relevant information from the field and potential analysis for further investigation.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It called on national governments to make use of WHO involvement whenever feasible, and absolved world governments in clear terms, saying that "No country should ever feel that any blame will attach to it for allowing an outbreak to occur".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of these Austrian wines were exported to West Germany, some of them in bulk to be bottled at large-scale West German bottling facilities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At these facilities, some Austrian wines were illegally blended into German wines by the importers, resulting in diethylene glycol ending up in some bulk-bottled West German wines.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The scandal was uncovered by wine laboratories performing quality controls on wines sold in West Germany and immediately made headlines worldwide.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The affected wines were immediately withdrawn from the market.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many involved in the scandal were sentenced to prison or heavy fines in Austria and West Germany.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The short-term effect of the scandal was a complete collapse of Austrian wine exports and a total loss of reputation of the entire Austrian wine industry, with a significant adverse impact on the reputation of German wines.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The long-term effect was that the Austrian wine industry focused their production on other wine types than previously, primarily dry white wines instead of sweet wines, and increasingly targeted a higher market segment.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Still, it took the Austrian wine industry over a decade to recover.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Austria also enacted much stricter wine laws.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At the time of the scandal, West Germany was the most important export market for Austrian wine and had been so for several years, with an increasing trend.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The Austrian wines exported to West Germany were of a similar style to those produced by West Germany itself, meaning semi-sweet and sweet white wines.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] However, many of these Austrian wines were focused on the low-cost segment, priced lower than German wines at the corresponding level of sweetness.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The traditional sweet wines of West Germany and Austria are produced from late harvest grapes, some of them affected by noble rot, and labelled in a hierarchy of Prädikat designations from Kabinett to Trockenbeerenauslese, depending on the ripeness of the grapes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Although sweet reserve (blending a wine with its own must) was allowed for the production of semi-sweet wines, no external sources of sugar were allowed for any wines with a Prädikat designation.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Thus, the production of wines at higher Prädikat levels tends to vary from year to year depending on vintage conditions, and all wines with higher designations sell at a premium price.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of the affordable sweet wines exported from Austria were blends from different grape varieties, and several of them did not carry any varietal designations, in contrast to the more expensive Prädikat wines of West Germany, which often were produced from Riesling grapes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Some Austrian exporters had entered into long-term contracts with supermarket chains to supply large quantities of wine at a specified quality level in terms of Prädikat.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] These producers encountered problems in some weak vintages, where much of the grape harvest did not reach sufficient ripeness levels.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At the levels of ripeness that were reached, the wines would be less sweet, less full-bodied, and more acidic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] One vintage plagued by these problems in Austria was 1982.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It is believed that when this led to insufficient quantities of wine being available to fulfill the contracts, some producers started to search for methods, including illegal ones, to "correct" the wines.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Simple sweetening (also illegal) would not necessarily do the job since it would not sufficiently correct the taste profile of the wine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] By using diethylene glycol (DEG), it was possible to affect both the impression of sweetness and the body of the wine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] German wine chemists have stated that it is unlikely that an individual winemaker of a small winery had sufficient chemical knowledge to devise the scheme, implying that the recipe must have been drawn up by a knowledgeable wine chemist consulting for a large-scale producer.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] DEG was otherwise used as an industrial chemical.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Adulteration of products with DEG has led to thousands of deaths worldwide since the first recorded case: the Elixir sulfanilamide incident in 1937.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] DEG was commonly misconceived of as being ethylene glycol, which is what is commonly understood as antifreeze, and is more toxic.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Most of the recalled wines contained up to a few grams of DEG per litre (and many only a fraction of a gram), which meant that dozens of bottles would have to be consumed in a limited period to reach the lethal dose of approximately 40 grams.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] However, in one record-setting wine (a 1981 Welschriesling Beerenauslese from Burgenland), 48 grams per litre was detected, which meant that the consumption of a single bottle could have been lethal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Also, long-term consumption of DEG is known to damage the kidney, liver, and brain.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The first wine discovered to contain DEG was a 1983 Ruster Auslese from a supermarket in Stuttgart, analysed on June 27, 1985.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Domestic wine fraud involving illegal sweetening had occurred earlier in West Germany and had led to investigations and prosecution of the winemakers involved.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] What made the 1985 findings very different was that a toxic compound had been used, and subsequent sampling indicated that many different bottlings were part of this dangerous adulteration scheme.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Therefore, unlike cases of simple sweetening, the 1985 DEG findings immediately took the proportion of a full-scale scandal requiring action by federal authorities in both West Germany and Austria.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] On July 9, the Federal Ministry of Health in Bonn issued an official health warning against the consumption of Austrian wines.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The findings immediately made headlines in West German media, and from there were cabled out throughout the world.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] From mid-July onward, selling Austrian wine on any export market was almost impossible.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Some countries like Switzerland and France confiscated thousands of bottles, and Japan introduced a ban on the import and sale of all Austrian wines on July 29, 1985.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In many other countries, wine dealers removed Austrian wines from shelves.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] From a pre-1985 level of around 45 million liters per year, exports immediately fell to one-tenth or roughly 4.4 million liters in 1986.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] They stayed at approximately the same level until 1989 and were slightly higher in 1990–97, but still well below pre-1985 levels.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Not until 2001 did the export volume, at just over 50 million liters, match the old level.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It thus took the Austrian wine industry fifteen years to regain its former position in terms of export volume, despite optimistic predictions from some quarters in Austria that it would all be forgotten in other countries in one year.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In the weeks following the breaking of the scandal, dozens of wine producers and dealers were arrested by Austrian authorities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The industry's practice of DEG adulteration was traced back to Otto Nadrasky, a 58-year-old chemist and wine consultant from Grafenwörth, Lower Austria.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The first prison sentence, of one and a half years, followed in mid-October.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of the adulterated wines were found to originate in Wagram in Lower Austria, where a consulting wine chemist was prosecuted.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] One of the convicted Wagram winemakers, Karl Grill, proprietor of *Firma Gebrüder Grill*, committed suicide after being sentenced.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The Parliament of Austria enacted a stricter wine law on August 29, 1985.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Having seen the immediate collapse of wine exports, the Austrian government rushed this legislation through parliament for it to be in effect before the 1985 harvest.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In West Germany, following a lengthy investigation, six former leading employees of the wholesale dealer and bottler Pieroth were sentenced to fines of one million Deutsche Marks by the *Landgericht* in Koblenz in April 1996.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Further legal action took place over the coming years across West Germany.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The case went through all three tiers of the administrative courts.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It was finally settled on October 18, 1990, when the Federal Administrative Court of Germany ruled against Pieroth and found that Geißler had the right to issue the list.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Thus, the legal status of the list was a crucial element in the many contract disputes.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] As a consequence of the scandal, a total of 27,000,000 litres of wine (corresponding to 36 million bottles or seven months' worth of Austria's total wine exports at the pre-1985 level) had to be destroyed by the West German authorities, which had confiscated or otherwise collected the wine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Doing this in an environmentally acceptable way proved challenging because DEG was incompatible with sewage treatment plants.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In the end, the wine was disposed of and destroyed by being poured into the ovens of a cement plant as a cooling agent instead of water.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In Austria, it was reported that the wine, mixed with other agents, was used as a road antifreeze in the particularly severe continental winter of February to March 1986.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The wine scandal has been the subject of many satirical references to Austrian wine inside Austria, in Germany, and beyond, and long after 1985.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Shortly after the scandal, the Styrian bard Volker Schöbitz composed a polka under the rhyming title *Zum Wohl, Glykol* – "Cheers, glycol".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] *Glykol* was also announced to be the 1985 Word of the Year in West Germany.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In *The Simpsons* season 1 episode "The Crepes of Wrath", a reference to the scandal is made when two Frenchmen with whom Bart is staying are arrested after putting antifreeze in wine and making Bart drink it.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] British rock band Half Man Half Biscuit reference the scandal in the song "RSVP" from their 2011 album *90 Bisodol (Crimond)*.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The **1992–1993 Jack in the Box *E. coli* outbreak** occurred when the *Escherichia coli* O157:H7 bacterium (originating from contaminated beef patties) killed 4 children and infected 732 people across four US states.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak involved 73 Jack in the Box restaurants in California, Idaho, Washington, and Nevada, and has been described as "far and away the most infamous food poison outbreak in contemporary history." The majority of the affected were under 10 years old.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] Four children died and 178 others were left with permanent injury including kidney and brain damage.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] On February 10, 1993, newly inaugurated President Bill Clinton participated in a televised town meeting program from the studios of WXYZ-TV in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] He fielded questions from the studio audience as well as studio audiences in Miami, Florida, and Seattle, and responded to questions from the parents of Riley Detwiler – the fourth and final child to die in the *E. coli* outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The wide media coverage and scale of the outbreak were responsible for "bringing the exotic-sounding bacterium out of the lab and into the public consciousness," but it was not the first *E. coli* O157:H7 outbreak resulting from undercooked patties.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The bacterium had previously been identified in an outbreak of food poisoning in 1982 (traced to undercooked burgers sold by McDonald's restaurants in Oregon and Michigan).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] Before the Jack in the Box incident, there had been 22 documented outbreaks in the United States resulting in 35 deaths.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla made and marketed unpasteurized fruit juices for the health segment of the juice market.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The Odwalla plant had several food safety issues, many of which arose because Odwalla did not pasteurize its juice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Tests discovered low levels of *Listeria monocytogenes*, a pathogen that can harm pregnant women, at the Odwalla factory in 1995.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In response, the company spent several million dollars on upgrading the plant's safety features, and bacteria were reduced to "relatively low levels".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The next year, Dave Stevenson, Odwalla's technical services director who oversaw quality assurance, suggested to Odwalla executives that the company should add a chlorine rinse to guard against bacteria on the skin of processed fruit, supplementing its existing phosphoric acid wash process.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] However, this plan was dropped by Chip Bettle, Odwalla's senior vice president, who feared that the chemicals would harm the fruit and alter the flavor of the juice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In a letter to *The New York Times* written on January 5, 1998, Odwalla's director of communications, Christopher C.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Gallagher, wrote that "Odwalla continuously upgraded its manufacturing process in the period leading up to the recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Moreover, our primary indicator of overall quality was daily bacteria-level readings, which were relatively low and decreasing in apple juice".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] On October 30, 1996, health officials from the state of Washington informed Odwalla that they had found a link between an outbreak of the *E. coli* O157:H7 bacterium and a batch of Odwalla's fresh apple juice produced on October 7.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] This was confirmed on November 5 and may have resulted from using rotten fruit; one account tells of fruit being used that was highly decayed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Another possible source of contamination was fallen apples ("grounders") that had come into contact with animal feces and had not been properly cleaned.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Confirmation that the bacteria came from outside the factory was provided when an inspection on November 15 found no evidence of *E. coli* contamination in the facility.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak came as a surprise as the plant had been inspected by the FDA three months earlier, and Odwalla supervisors were not aware that the *E. coli* bacteria could grow in acidic, chilled apple juice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Based on a recommendation from the FDA, on October 30, Odwalla's Chief Executive Officer Stephen Williamson voluntarily recalled 13 products which contained apple juice from about 4,600 stores.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Carrot and vegetable juices were also recalled the following day as a precautionary measure since they were processed on the same line.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The recall cost the company $6.5 million and took around 48 hours to complete, with almost 200 trucks being dispatched to collect the recalled products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla opened a website and a call center to handle consumer questions about the recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] As a result of the outbreak, 16-month-old Anna Gimmestad of Greeley, Colorado died from kidney failure, and more than 60 people became sick.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Fourteen children were hospitalized with hemolytic-uremic syndrome, a severe kidney and blood disorder, and were, according to doctors, "likely to have permanent kidney damage and other lasting problems".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In consequence, Odwalla stock fell by forty percent, and sales of its products dropped by ninety percent.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The company laid off 60 workers, and, at the end of the fiscal year, posted a loss of $11.3 million.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak occurred because Odwalla sold unpasteurized fruit juices, though pasteurization had long been standard in the juice industry, claiming that pasteurization alters the flavor and destroys at least 30% of nutrients and enzymes in fruit juice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Instead, Odwalla relied on washing usable fruit with sanitizing chemicals before pressing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla pleaded guilty, and was fined $1.5 million: at the time, the most significant penalty in a food poisoning case in the United States.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] With the judge's permission, Odwalla donated $250,000 of the $1.5 million to fund research in preventing food-borne illnesses.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] William "Bill" Marler represented several children who developed hemolytic-uremic syndrome and suffered severe kidney damage as a result of the outbreak.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Most of the claims were resolved in early 2000, and in addition to the fines, the company spent roughly another $12 million settling the lawsuits from the families whose children were infected.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] To boost sales following the recall, Odwalla reformulated five products to remove their apple juice content and re-released them in November 1996.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Flash pasteurization, as well as several other safety precautions, were introduced to the manufacturing process, and the juices reappeared on store shelves on December 5, 1996.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The **2008 Chinese milk scandal** was a significant food safety incident in China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal involved Sanlu Group's milk and infant formula along with other food materials and components being adulterated with the chemical melamine, which resulted in kidney stones and other kidney damage in infants.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The chemical was used to increase the nitrogen content of diluted milk, giving it the appearance of higher protein content in order to pass quality control testing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] 300,000 affected children were identified, among which 54,000 were hospitalized, according to the latest report in January 2009.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The deaths of six babies were officially concluded to be related to the contaminated milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The timeline of the scandal dated back to December 2007, when Sanlu began to receive complaints about kidney stones.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An early complaint was made on 20 May 2008, when a mother posted online after she learnt that Sanlu had donated the milk she had been complaining about to the orphans of the 2008 Sichuan earthquake.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Also on 20 May, the problem was raised at Sanlu's Board meeting for the first time and they ordered multiple third-party tests.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The culprit, melamine, was undetected in the tests until 1 August.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] New Zealand dairy giant Fonterra, which owned a 43% stake in Sanlu, were alerted to the contamination on 2 August.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Fonterra alerted the New Zealand government and the NZ government confronted the Chinese government on 8 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Chinese government made the scandal public on 13 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] After the initial focus on Sanlu, further government inspections revealed that products from 21 other companies were also tainted, including those from Arla Foods–Mengniu, Yili, and Yashili.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] While more and more cases reached hospitals around the nation from December 2007, the first report to the government by any hospital was made on 16 July.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The issue raised concerns about food safety and political corruption in China and damaged the reputation of the country's food exports.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The World Health Organization called the incident "deplorable" and at least 11 foreign countries halted all imports of Chinese dairy products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The former chairwoman of China's Sanlu dairy was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late October 2008, similar adulteration with melamine was discovered in eggs and possibly other foods.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The source was traced to melamine being added to animal feed, despite a ban imposed in June 2007 following the scandal over pet food ingredients exported to the United States.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is used to manufacture melamine-formaldehyde resin, a type of plastic known for its flame-retardant properties and commonly employed in countertops, dry-erase boards, etc.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It has also been employed as a non-protein nitrogen, appearing in soy meal, corn gluten meal and cottonseed meal used in cattle feed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is known to cause kidney failure and kidney stones in humans and animals when it reacts with cyanuric acid inside the body.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The use of melamine in food production is not approved by the World Health Organization (WHO) or national authorities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is nitrogen-rich, so it is sometimes illegally added to food products to increase their apparent protein content.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Kjeldahl and Dumas methods used to test for protein levels fail to distinguish between nitrogen in melamine and naturally occurring nitrogen in amino acids, allowing the protein levels to be falsified.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Introduced into milk, it can help conceal fraudulent dilution with water.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine adulteration of food products also made headlines when pet food was recalled in Europe and the U.S. in 2007.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) said melamine may be found "in a variety of milk and milk products at varying levels, from low ppb to ppm ranges".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] One academic suggested cyromazine, a melamine derivative pesticide commonly used in China for a long time, is absorbed into plants as melamine; it may therefore have long been present in products such as poultry, eggs, fish, and dairy products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It is not known where in the supply chain the melamine was added to the milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The chemical is not water-soluble, and must be mixed with formaldehyde or another chemical before it can be dissolved in milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of poor animal husbandry, production and storage and the demand for milk far outstripping supplies, the use of other potentially harmful chemical additives such as preservatives and hydrogen peroxide has been reported by independent media as being commonplace.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Quality tests can be falsified with additives: peroxide is added to prevent milk from going bad; industrial vegetable oil is emulsified and added to boost fat levels; whey is used to increase lactose content.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, the procurement chain is also implicated, as milk agents are often politically well-connected.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Farmers report salespeople had, for years, been visiting farms in dairy areas hawking "protein powder" additives, which would often be delivered in unmarked brown paper bags of 25 kilograms (55 lb) each.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Thus, farmers either added melamine contaminant unwittingly, or turned a blind eye to milk adulteration to ensure their milk was not rejected.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The big dairy producers were complicit in producing "test-tube milk".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 17 September 2008, Health Minister Chen Zhu stated tainted milk formula had "sickened more than 6,200 children, and that more than 1,300 others, mostly newborns, remain hospitalized with 158 suffering from acute kidney failure".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] By 23 September, about 54,000 children were reported to be sick and four had died.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An additional 10,000 cases were reported from the provinces by 27 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A World Health Organization official said 82% of the children made ill were 2 years of age or below.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Hong Kong Centre for Food Safety said that 99 per cent of the victims were aged under 3 years.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Ten Hong Kong children were diagnosed with kidney problems, at least four cases were detected in Macau, and six in Taiwan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Non-human casualties included a lion cub and two baby orangutans which had been fed Sanlu infant formula at Hangzhou Zoo.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The government said on 8 October it would no longer issue updated figures "because it is not an infectious disease, so it's not absolutely necessary for us to announce it to the public".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Reuters compiled figures reported by local media across the country, and said the toll stood at nearly 94,000 at the end of September, excluding municipalities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Notably, 13,459 children had been affected in Gansu, Reuters quoted Xinhua saying Henan had reported over 30,000 cases, and Hebei also had nearly 16,000 cases.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late October, the government announced health officials had surveyed 300,000 Beijing families with children less than 3 years old.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It disclosed approximately 74,000 families had a child who had been fed melamine-tainted milk, but did not reveal how many of those children had fallen ill as a result.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of the many months before the scandal was exposed, media suggested the official figures were likely to be understated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Kidney stones in infants started being reported in several parts of China in the two years prior.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A number of yet-to-be-officially-acknowledged cases were reported by the media.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, those deaths without an official verdict may be denied compensation.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On characterisation and treatment of urinary stones in affected infants, the *New England Journal of Medicine* printed an editorial in March 2009, along with reports on cases from Beijing, Hong Kong and Taipei.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Urinary calculi specimens were collected from 15 cases treated in Beijing and were analysed as unknown objects for their components at Beijing Institute of Microchemistry using infrared spectroscopy, nuclear magnetic resonance, and high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The result of the analyses showed the calculi were composed of melamine and uric acid, and the molecular ratio of uric acid to melamine was around 2:1.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In a study published in 2010, researchers from Peking University studying ultrasound images of infants who fell ill in the 2008 contamination found while most children in a rural Chinese area recovered, 12 per cent still showed kidney abnormalities six months later.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] "The potential for long-term complications after exposure to melamine remains a serious concern", the report said.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Contaminated products found in the China AQSIS tests include baby formula products produced by the following companies, in order of highest concentration found.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal began with revelations of contamination of Sanlu milk products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The New Zealand dairy cooperative Fonterra, which owned a 43% stake in Sanlu, said they were alerted to melamine contamination on 2 August (almost a month before the issue became public), and have said to have pushed hard for a full public recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Although there was an immediate trade recall, Fonterra said that local administrators refused an official recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A Fonterra director had given Sanlu management a document detailing the European Union's permitted levels of melamine, but Fonterra chief executive Andrew Ferrier has stated that at no time did Fonterra say small amounts of melamine were acceptable.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] From 2005 to 2006, an agent, Jiang Weisuo, from Shaanxi Jinqiao Dairy Company in northern China reportedly publicly discussed his fears about unauthorised substances being added to competitors' milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The paediatrician, who specifically asked the AQSIQ to refer his observations to epidemiologists, was asked to refer his query to the health department.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In June, Jiangsu media reported a two-month surge in the number of babies diagnosed with kidney disease; in July, a parent of a sick baby in Hunan questioned Sanlu's powdered milk and complained to the AQSIQ.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Gansu Province sent a report to the Ministry of Health on 16 July to alert that one local hospital had identified an increase in the incidence of kidney ailments among babies in the months earlier, and that most victims had consumed Sanlu's baby formula.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The health ministry sent investigators to Gansu in early August.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Fonterra notified the New Zealand government on 5 September and three days later, Prime Minister Helen Clark had Beijing officials alerted directly.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] News reports began circulating in China on 9 September, and the news was broken internationally by Reuters the following day.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The state-controlled media report did not initially identify the company involved.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Posts on Chinese social portal Tianya named Sanlu as the culprit, which Sanlu denied.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to a State Council investigation, Sanlu had known about infants made sick by its products as early as December 2007, but no testing was performed until June 2008.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It said leading government officials in Shijiazhuang city had failed to report the contamination to provincial and state authorities (until 9 September) in violation of rules on reporting major incidents involving food safety.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to the *People's Daily*, on 2 August, Sanlu asked the Shijiazhuang city government to assist them in controlling the media's reporting of the recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to accounts confirmed by media reports and health officials, the company tried to buy off critics and cover up the contamination.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In a memo dated 11 August, Beijing-based public relations agency Teller International advised Sanlu to seek cooperation with major search engines to censor negative information.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The agency reportedly had repeatedly contacted key account staff at Baidu and proposed a ¥3 million (US$440,000) budget to screen all negative news.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] After the memo began circulating on the internet, Baidu denounced, in a communiqué on 13 September 2008, the approaches by said agency on several occasions, saying the proposal was firmly rejected, as it violated their corporate principles of unbiased and transparent reporting.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark said that she believed the Chinese government had been inclined to try to solve the problem quietly, without a recall.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Central government denied issuing this guidance.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Hebei provincial vice-governor said his administration was only notified by Shijiazhuang on 8 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, a journalist at *Southern Weekend* wrote an investigative report in late July for publication about infants who had fallen ill after consuming baby formula from Sanlu.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Six weeks later, senior editor Fu Jianfeng made a post on his personal blog stating that this report had been suppressed by authorities because of the imminent Beijing Olympics.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] While this was happening, Sanlu was honoured in a national award campaign called "30 Years: Brands that Have Changed the Lives of Chinese".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The press release on the award, written by a senior public relations manager at Sanlu, passed as news content on *People's Daily* and in other media.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 15 September, the company issued a public apology for the contaminated powdered milk; Sanlu was ordered to halt production, and to destroy all unsold and recalled products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Authorities reportedly seized 2,176 tons of powdered milk in Sanlu's warehouses.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An estimated 9,000 tons of product had been recalled.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Shijiazhuang Mayor Ji Chuntang resigned on 17 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Li Changjiang, minister in charge of the AQSIQ, was forced to resign on 22 September after the State Council inquest concluded he was responsible for the "negligence in supervision".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Investigators also blamed the Shijiazhuang government.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Local Party Secretary Wu Xianguo was fired on the same day.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Sanlu general manager Tian Wenhua was charged under Articles 144 and 150 of the criminal code.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A spokesman for the Hebei Provincial Public Security Department said police had arrested 12 milk dealers and suppliers who allegedly sold contaminated milk to Sanlu, and six people were charged with selling melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Three hundred kg (700 lb) of suspicious chemicals, including 223 kg (492 lb) of melamine, were confiscated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Among those arrested were two brothers who ran a milk collection centre in Hebei for allegedly supplying three tonnes of adulterated milk daily to the dairy; the owner of another collection centre which resold seven tons of milk a day to Sanlu, was arrested, and his operation was shut down.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang Yujun (alias Zhang Haitao), a former dairy farmer from Hebei, produced more than 600 tons of a "protein powder" mixture of melamine and maltodextrin from September 2007 to August 2008.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] He and eight other traders, dairy farm owners and milk purchasers who bought the powder from him were arrested in early October, bringing the total to 36.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] During the week of 22 December 2008, 17 people involved in producing, selling, buying and adding melamine in raw milk went on trial.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tian Wenhua, former Sanlu general manager, and three other company executives appeared in court in Shijiazhuang, charged with producing and selling milk contaminated with melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to *Xinhua*, Tian pleaded guilty, and told the court she learned about the tainted milk complaints from consumers in mid-May.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] She then apparently headed a working team to handle the case, but did not report to the Shijiazhuang city government until 2 August.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Intermediate People's Court in Shijiazhuang sentenced Zhang Yujun and Geng Jinping to death, and Tian Wenhua to life in prison, on 22 January 2009.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang was convicted for producing 800 tons of the contaminated powder, Geng for producing and selling toxic food.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Geng Jinping managed a milk production center which supplied milk to Sanlu Group and other dairies.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The *China Daily* reported Geng had knelt on the courtroom floor and begged the victim's families for forgiveness during the trial.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The court also sentenced Sanlu deputy general managers Wang Yuliang and Hang Zhiqi to fifteen years and eight years in jail, respectively, and former manager Wu Jusheng to five years.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang Yujun and Geng Jinping were executed on 24 November 2009.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tian Wenhua received several sentence reductions for good conduct over the years.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In 2011, her life term was reduced to 19 years.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Further reductions have since lowered that sentence to 15 years and three months.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The value of the company plunged as a result of the scandal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 24 September, Fonterra announced it had written down the carrying value of its investment by NZ$139 million (two-thirds), reflecting the costs of product recall and the impairment of the 'Sanlu' brand because of the "criminal contamination of milk".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] By 27 September, *China Daily* reported Sanlu was close to bankruptcy, and might be taken over by the Beijing Sanyuan Foods Company.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The company is also facing lawsuits from parents (see *Anger at Sanlu*).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 25 December, Shijiazhuang court accepted a creditor's bankruptcy petition against Sanlu.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Media commentators expected the Sanlu distribution network to be sold.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 16 September, the AQSIQ released test of samples from 491 batches of products sold by all 109 companies producing baby formula.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It said all 11 samples from Sanlu failed the melamine test.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Sanlu, whose products sell at half the price of equivalents on the market, recorded the highest levels of contamination among all the samples tested, at 2,563 mg/kg or parts per million ("ppm").
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tainted samples were found among 21 other suppliers, where concentrations ranged from 0.09 to 619.00 ppm.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] There was melamine contamination in 10% of liquid milk samples from Mengniu and Yili, and 6% of those from Bright Dairy.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On discovery of contamination, the three major producers were all stripped of their status as 'Chinese national brands'.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Yili, Mengniu and Bright Dairy & Food Co. recalled tainted powdered milk and apologised in separate statements.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu recalled all its baby formula, and trading in its shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange was suspended on 17 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Shares in other dairy companies fell strongly the next day.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu's CFO attempted to reassure consumers by offering a no-quibble refund on all products, and by drinking liquid milk in front of reporters in Hong Kong.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] He also said that its export products were less likely to be contaminated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 30 September, the AQSIQ announced test results of a further 265 batches of powdered milk produced by 154 different companies prior to 14 September, where it found 31 batches produced by 20 domestic dairy companies were tainted with melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 1 December, China's Ministry of Health issued an update, saying nearly 300,000 babies were sickened after consuming melamine-contaminated infant formula.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The State Council ordered the testing of product of all dairy producers, and to this end, some 5,000 inspectors were dispatched.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Chinese market has grown at an average annual rate of 23% since 2000.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In 2006, milk production reached 30 million tons, ten times the volume of a decade before.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It was valued at some ¥122 billion (US$18 billion) in 2007, and consumers had severely lost confidence in the industry.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The events have exposed the often-incestuous relationship between local business and local government.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal has also highlighted structural problems of inadequate production volume, inherent quality issues, and poor production methods.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Inner Mongolia region produces over one-fourth of China's milk, and Mengniu and Yili have invested millions to establish state-of-the-art dairy facilities in its capital, Hohhot.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The companies still rely on small-scale farmers for over 90% of their production because of the capacity constraint of the modern facilities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Both companies were said by farmers and agents to have habitually purchased milk which failed quality tests, for only two-thirds the normal price.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A new policy was put in place on 17 September to stop that practice.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Consumer panic resulting from the contaminated milk lessened demand for dairy products, causing hardship to more than 2 million Chinese farmers who had nowhere to sell their milk and no means by which to support their dairy cows.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Farmers reportedly poured away milk and faced selling cows to a buyerless market.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the scandal erupted, sales have fallen by 30–40% on a comparative basis, according to the Chinese Dairy Association.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Association estimates the financial effect of the order of ¥20 billion, and forecasts that confidence may take up to two years to be fully restored.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In an effort to prop up sales and retain their market share, dairy firms have cancelled their common accord not to use promotions to fight the sales decline: substantial discounts (including BOGOF), free gifts and other point of sale incentives were being offered to shoppers.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Their new products are conspicuously labelled "safety inspection passed" to allay consumer fears.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu-Arla, a joint-venture between Danish/Swedish co-operative Arla Foods and Mengniu halted production on 16 September 2008 after three of 28 tests taken from Mengniu showed traces of melamine; the contaminated batches had been recalled.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu, milk supplier to Starbucks, was replaced by Vitasoy when the coffee retailer eschewed milk in favour of soya milk in its China operations.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] KFC also suspended selling Mengniu milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Seoul-headquartered Lotte Group, a major snacks maker, recalled its Koala's March cookies in Hong Kong and Macau because of contamination, and promised to "look deeply into all the details of the manufacturing process" to preserve customer confidence.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The range was also ordered off Dutch and Slovak shelves.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Other products were seized when samples tested positive in Malta.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 29 September, British confectionery group Cadbury recalled all chocolate products made in its Chinese factories due to concerns about melamine contamination, affecting products intended for markets in China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Japan, Korea and Australia.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tests in Hong Kong found amounts of melamine in China-made Dairy Milk products which exceeded safety regulations.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 30 September, Unilever recalled its Lipton milk tea powder after the company's internal checks found traces of melamine in the Chinese powdered milk used as an ingredient.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Heinz recalled cases of baby cereal in Hong Kong after discovering they contained melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Nestlé's factory in Heilongjiang was also implicated: the Taiwanese Department of Health forced the delisting of six *Neslac* and *KLIM* products on 2 October for containing minute traces of melamine, although the minister said they did not pose a significant health risk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the milk crisis broke, Nestlé says it has sent 20 specialists from Switzerland to five of its Chinese plants to strengthen chemical testing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 31 October, it announced the opening of a $10.2 million Beijing research and development centre, to "serve as the base and the reference in food safety for Nestlé in Greater China".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Nestlé Chief Technology Officer said the centre was equipped with "highly sophisticated analytical tools for detecting trace amounts of residues and undesirable compounds like melamine or veterinary drugs or natural toxins".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] There were concerns dairy products consumed during the 2008 Summer Olympics may have been contaminated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Li Changjiang, the then Director of AQSIQ reassured the international community that all the food, including dairy products, was indeed safe.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] PRC Customs said exports of dairy products and eggs in 2007 were valued at US$359 million, a year-on-year increase of 90 per cent.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the news of the melamine contamination began to circulate, at least 25 countries stopped importing Chinese dairy products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal led to an erosion of trust in locally produced infant formula and from then on, many Shenzhen residents and parallel traders travelled across the border to purchase powdered milk from Hong Kong shops.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Lower confidence in mainland Chinese production, combined with the relaxation of visa requirements for mainland residents, had resulted in shortages of infant formula in Hong Kong for an extended time.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of a great public outcry, the Import and Export (General) (Amendment) Regulation 2013 was passed in Hong Kong, prohibiting the unlicensed export of powdered formula, including milk and soya milk powder for infants and children under 36 months.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Although the Hong Kong government imposed a strict 2-can limit on the export of infant formula in March 2013, spurred price differentials caused by sales tax on the mainland and lax customs, trafficking activity including for powdered milk has continued, exacerbating the Hong Kong-Mainland conflict.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The catchment area for traffickers spread from Fan Ling and Sheung Shui southward to Yuen Long and Tuen Mun, causing localist camp such as Civic Passion and Hong Kong Indigenous to take to the streets in direct action in 2015.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 25 September 2008, the EU announced a ban on imports of baby food containing Chinese milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In the United States of America, which was otherwise unaffected by the scares, the US distributor of White Rabbit candies recalled the product when samples found in Hartford showed traces of melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The candy's maker and subsidiary of Bright Foods, Guan Sheng Yuan, issued a recall to the 50 countries to which it exported.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Food and Drug Administration said while food containing melamine below 2.5 parts per million generally did not raise concerns, its scientists were "currently unable to establish any level of melamine and melamine-related compounds in infant formula that does not raise public health concerns".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late November, after the FDA found traces of melamine in one Nestle and one Mead Johnson infant product, the FDA concluded melamine or cyanuric acid alone, "at or below 1 part per million in infant formula do not raise public health concerns" in babies.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The United States Food and Drug Administration opened its first overseas inspection offices in November 2008, with bureaus in Shanghai, Beijing and Guangzhou.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) warned that children who ate large amounts of confectionery and biscuits with high milk content could theoretically be consuming melamine at more than three times above prescribed EU safety limits (0.5 mg/kg of body weight).
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The EFSA said children with a mean consumption of products such as milk toffee, biscuits and chocolate containing contaminated powdered milk would not be at risk, and adults would not be at risk even in the worst-case scenarios.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The World Health Organization, which was only notified on 11 September, asked Beijing why it took so many months for the scandal to become public, and to establish whether failure was deliberate or due to ignorance.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO's representative in China, Hans Troedsson, said the issue of who knew what and when was critical, because knowledge would be the distinction between ignorance and neglect.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following a spate of mass national bans, the WHO urged national food safety authorities on 25 September to test Chinese dairy products for health risks before placing import bans or recalls.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 26 September, the WHO warned health officials to look out for tainted dairy products imported from China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] International Food Safety Authorities (INFOSAN), a network organized by WHO and the Food and Agriculture Organization, suggested that countries should focus on smuggled formula.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO referred to the incident as one of the largest food safety events it has had to deal with, and stated it would be difficult to restore the confidence of Chinese consumers in baby formula.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It saw regulation failing to keep pace with the rapid development of the food and industrial production as opening the gates to all types of misbehaviour and malfeasance.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The spokesman said the scale of the problem proved it was "clearly not an isolated accident, [but] a large-scale intentional activity to deceive consumers for simple, basic, short-term profits".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO Director-General Margaret Chan reminded Chinese mothers that breastfeeding was the best way to provide nutrition to infants while avoiding a risk of melamine exposure.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] She noted that the scandal showed "the impact and power of globalisation" in food distribution and highlighted "the importance of seamless cooperation from farm to consumer".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The case has brought anger and resentment towards milk producers and sowed uncertainty and confusion amongst the population.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Queues formed outside Sanlu's offices for refunds.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As has been increasingly common practice, web users vented their anger on internet bulletin boards.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Prevalent food scares have increased the number of online parodies circulated by netizens.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Before the government began offering free medical treatment, some parents had reportedly spent small fortunes on medical care for their sick children.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Children who fell ill before the scandal broke on 12 September were not entitled to free medical care offered by the State.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Parents of two such victims, one from Henan and one from Guangdong, filed writs against Sanlu despite government pressure.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Parents of the Henan child had claimed ¥150,000 for medical, travel and other expenses incurred after their child developed kidney stones.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 20 October, the parents of one baby who died from contaminated milk appealed to New Zealand for justice on TV ONE.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A total of nine cases were filed against Sanlu in Shijiazhuang.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following weeks of discussions, and in the absence of a compensation plan, a group of 15 lawyers filed a class-action lawsuit on behalf of 100 families against Sanlu, seeking medical and other expenses as well as compensation for trauma and for death of an offspring.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Resentment increased towards the country's leaders due to the perception that they were not troubled by the food security turmoil faced by ordinary citizens.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Poorer consumers reliant on local infant formula, which was approximately half the price of imported brands, had been left without alternatives to feed their children.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Many had lost faith in local brands, with others unsure of which brands were safe.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Supermarket shelves had been swept bare from product recalls.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Shops in Hong Kong reported a rush for imported formula from cross-border shoppers, with some retailers reportedly rationing their stocks.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some mainlanders were also reportedly rushing to import infant formula from Kinmen.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wet nurses enjoyed a resurgence in popularity in major cities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some media reports have documented that Chinese sailors and expatriates have been buying local dairy produce in Australia to send back to relatives in China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It had been estimated in 2018 that up to 80% to 90% of infant formula purchased in Australia was destined for China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following widespread complaints and appeals by exasperated Australian parents unable to find formula for their children, Coles supermarkets resorted to locking baby formula tins away behind the Service Counter, like tobacco products, in order to regulate their sale.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The two major supermarkets, Coles and Woolworths, placed a two item limit on baby formula purchases to curb the growing practice of bulk purchasing by predominantly Chinese customers known as *daigou*, or "personal shoppers".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] These people would often travel in large, organised groups from supermarket to supermarket, clearing the shelves of baby formula, then make substantial profits by sending the formula to China to be sold at a significant markup.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Protesters fearful at reunification blamed the Kuomintang for the melamine scare, and criticised it for failing to stand up to China over the contamination.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] One citizen voiced concern that President Ma Ying-jeou's promise for closer ties with China would bring in more tainted products to Taiwan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Minister of the Department of Health, Lin Fang-yue, was heavily criticised for raising the legally acceptable limit of melamine in food products from zero to 2.5 ppm.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The public outcry subsequent to the move forced Lin to resign.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] His successor, Yeh Ching-chuan, announced a return to the original zero-tolerance policy to melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] AQSIQ announced the revocation of all exemptions from inspection previously granted to dairy producers, who were asked to cease citing the privilege in their advertisements.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The State Council ordered an overhaul of the dairy industry, and promised to provide free medical care to those affected.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Formally, the State Council released its initial findings, and a top-level official apology of the incident both came on 21 September.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wen Jiabao apologised while visiting victims in hospitals.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 6 October 2008, putting the blame on "illegal production and greed", the country's "chaotic dairy production and distribution order", and the "gravely absent supervision" for the crisis, the State Council announced new dairy industry regulations.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On November 19, 2008, the State Council promulgated the "China Dairy Industry Reorganization and Revitalization Plan" to rectify the chaos in China's dairy industry.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 9 October 2008, in an attempt to control the damage to Chinese dairy exports, officials at a World Trade Organization meeting insisted that contamination had been "accidental", directly contradicting the WHO observations.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Chinese trade representatives criticised countries which have imposed blanket bans on Chinese food products.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They urged member states to base import restrictions on scientific risk assessments, and to use official WTO notification mechanisms.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 11 October, Deputy Health minister Liu Qian stated that all the foreign companies' application for compensation for dairy products recall would be dealt with on a commercial basis, although government may use diplomatic channels if necessary, if problems were encountered.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to a senior quality inspectorate official, the government aimed to establish nearly 400 product testing centres within the next two years, and 80 of these would be food testing centres.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Working groups were established in nearly every single province in order to set up new food testing centres and replace outdated equipment.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 24 September 2008, China's newly appointed AQSIQ chief Wang Yong said that the government would "carry out 'forceful' measures to deal with the chemical contamination", and stated that inspectors had removed 7,000 tonnes of melamine-contaminated dairy products from shops all over China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The ministry was reported to have investigated 98 dairy producers and farms, banned 151 illegal companies and indicted three manufacturers for feed containing melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] During an investigation into melamine contamination at Yili and Mengniu in Hohhot, police arrested six more people for allegedly selling and mixing melamine into raw milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The AQSIQ announced on 5 October that all tests showed all milk produced after 14 September were free from contamination.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine stated all dairy products made before 14 September will be tested for melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They gave notice to all supermarkets, shops, and all city, town and village-level vendors to urgently remove and seal up all powdered milk and liquid milk made before 14 September, pending further testing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A researcher at the Chinese Centre for Disease Control and Prevention said that any amount exceeding 1 ppm would give reason to suspect its presence was intentional.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 16 September, the AQSIQ tests on baby milk powder produced by 109 companies showed 69 batches from 22 companies to be melamine-contaminated; the State Council attempted to reassure that formula produced by most companies in China was safe.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 16 September, the AQSIQ published results of tests on 408 liquid milk producers, and found "most dairy products were safe to drink", although the test results showed nearly 10 percent of batches from Mengniu, Yili and Bright were contaminated.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] To demonstrate that its emergency measures had been effective, the Ministry of Agriculture said the rate of raw milk dumping because of the contamination scandal has decreased from 23.6% on 22 September to 4.6% on 1 October.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] During the scandal, China's media was ordered to tone down coverage of the unfolding scandal to prevent unrest.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] News editors were told to adhere to the official copy provided by China's state news agency, *Xinhua News Agency*, and to emphasize other news instead.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] China Central Television shifted its reporting emphasis to the launch of Shenzhou VII, with the announcement of the AQSIQ test results relegated to the final item on the CCTV evening news.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As a result of media suppression, Chinese consumers were ill-informed about the extent of global recalls.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to Chinese journalists, discussion of the causes of the crisis, government responsibility, questions about government complicity with dairy companies, was forbidden.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 2 January, a website created by individuals protesting against Sanlu was also blocked by the authorities.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A group of parents whose children were rendered ill by melamine-contaminated milk held a news conference to draw attention to the plight of their sick children; five were allegedly detained by police and taken to a labour camp outside Beijing.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] In 2012, Jiang Weisuo, a 44-year-old general manager of a dairy products plant in Shaanxi province, was rumoured to have been murdered in Xi'an city.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It was Jiang who had first alerted authorities to the scandal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to the Xi'an Evening News, Jiang died in hospital on 12 November from knife wounds inflicted by his wife, Yang Ping, but the purported murder by his wife was subsequently reported to be incorrect.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A group of 90 lawyers from Hebei, Henan and Shandong—the three worst affected provinces—had made *pro bono* offers to assist victims, and a list of their names was published.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Organisers of the group declared that they had come under pressure from officials to not get involved in the issue.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Beijing Lawyers' Association, a part of the Communist Party apparatus, asked its members "to put faith in the party and government".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Other members of the group have reportedly received less subtle requests.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Authorities are said to fear social unrest if lawsuits were unleashed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Pro-Beijing Hong Kong journal *Ta Kung Pao* reported that central authorities, fearful of the effect of mass lawsuits, held a meeting with lawyers' groups on 14 September, asking them to "act together, and help maintain stability".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Chang Boyang, one of the group of volunteer lawyers, said he had filed one suit in Guangdong against Sanlu on behalf of the parents of one victim, and another suit in Henan.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to Chang, the justice department of Henan ordered 14 Henan lawyers to drop their cases and "follow the arrangements set out by the government".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An official said that central government had issued instructions placing the cases on hold, pending a decision on how to handle the cases in a unified manner.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Furthermore, that court was instructed not to give any written replies or accept Sanlu-related cases in the meantime.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Stratfor believed that the act of adulterating milk and baby food in full knowledge of potentially severe sanctions, including execution, seemed like "an act of desperation".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It noted that in 2008 dairy farmers became squeezed by growing costs of livestock, feed, facilities, and government-imposed price caps.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Mengniu's share price had fallen 12% since October 2007 because of higher costs of raw milk (due partly to rising costs of cattle feed) and price controls—anti-inflation measures targeted at the dairy sector announced on 16 January.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Milk suppliers accordingly resorted to subtler cost-cutting methods to preserve diminishing profits.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Joseph Sternberg of *The Wall Street Journal* said that Beijing's failures of food-safety act are "much more pernicious, and disgraceful, than at first it appears ... [not only has this] milk poisoned thousands of infants with melamine, it also poisons the society at large with fear".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Lawyer Bill Marler, speaking at a food safety conference in Beijing, said that this food scare has harmed the "made in China" brand abroad.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An op-ed in *The New York Times* compared this to the "swill milk scandal" in New York in the 1850s in which 8,000 children reportedly died when cows were fed swill and the milk produced was then whitened with plaster of Paris, thickened with starch and eggs, and hued with molasses.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An article published in the *San Francisco Chronicle* likened the regulatory failures of the milk scandal to the distressed assets in the subprime mortgage crisis, and questioned whether regulators in either case ever understood or truly monitored the extent of the danger.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 10 November 2008 issue of the Singaporean newspaper *Today*, Bill Durodié, then a senior fellow at the S.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The structure of the Chinese government was criticized for contributing to the scandal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] *Time* magazine cited analysts saying the party's need to maintain control of the economy and of information undermines the independence of any regulatory system.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] One analyst, Willy Lam, a Senior Fellow at The Jamestown Foundation, indicated that CCP's pervasive control over political and economic resources has resulted in a lack of accountability in government systems.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A Beijing-based consultancy, Dragonomics, concurred that "the problem was rooted in the Communist Party's continued involvement in pricing control, company management and the flow of information".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Independent regulation was lacking or ineffective as local industries were so intertwined with local officialdom.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Access Asia, a Shanghai-based consumer consultancy, said Fonterra was an example of western executives in China "believ[ing] advice in business books that they must avoid making their local partners 'lose face' at all costs".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It suggested that Fonterra paid the price for this both financially and in damage to their reputation.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] David Bandurski, journalist and researcher at China Media Project, criticised the state's control of the media for suppressing "information critical to the well-being of ordinary Chinese".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] He asserted that increased press freedom needs to be a component of any strategy to deal with this and other future food-security lapses in China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Bandurski cited warnings on 9 October 2008 issues of *Nanfang Daily* and the *Information Times* for consumers to be aware of that problematic dairy stock (that produced before 14 September) have reappeared in some stores under cover of aggressive promotions.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Former senior party official Bao Tong said "the more dark secrets are exposed, the better.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] You can't cure the disease, or save the Chinese people, until you get to the root of the problem." "If the Chinese government tries to play down this incident, there will be no social stability in China, let alone harmony ...
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As a reaction to and comment on the scandal, Chinese artist and video animation producer Pi San created "Little Rabbit, Be Good" as part of his popular Kuang Kuang video series.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Though officially banned or forbidden by the Chinese government, clever use of Chinese web services such as Baidu allows Chinese citizens to access this and many other forbidden materials.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] This daigou activity has been facilitated by the Chinese Navy and its warships.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The search widened when some manufacturers tested positive despite reportedly not using Chinese milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Japanese and South Korean authorities' tests on imported powdered eggs from China found melamine contamination.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Japan found melamine in frozen fried chicken imported from China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The South Korean supplies were traced to two companies in Dalian.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 26 October, Hong Kong authorities discovered 4.7ppm melamine in eggs from Dalian.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Hong Kong Secretary for Food and Health, York Chow, suspected the melamine came from feed given to the chickens that laid the eggs.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 29 October, Hong Kong authorities discovered a third batch of eggs containing excessive melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Taiwanese Department of Health said that six batches of protein powder from Jilin and Dalian were found to contain 1.90 to 5.03ppm of melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Agriculture officials speculated that adulterated feed given to hens could explain melamine in eggs.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Web sites of *Xinhua* and *People's Daily* both carried a story from the *Nanfang Daily* that mixing melamine into animal feed was an "open secret" in the industry: melamine scrap was mixed into an inexpensive "protein powder" resold to feed suppliers.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] People in the trade interviewed by *BusinessWeek* also confirmed it was common practice, and had been going on for "years", with most believing it to be non-toxic to animals.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Melamine dealers said after Sanlu, the government started clamping down on melamine sales to food processing companies or to manufacturers of animal feed.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Malaysian authorities determined that ammonium bicarbonate, not milk, imported from China was the source of contamination at the Khong Guan and Khian Guan biscuit factory.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Malaysian authorities said it was probable cross contamination of batches from Chinese companies Broadtech Chemical Int.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Co Ltd, Dalian Chemical Industries and Tianjin Red Triangle International Trading Co, and did not suspect adulteration.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 19 October, Taiwanese authorities detected melamine in 469 tons of ammonium bicarbonate imported from China.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Samples tested showed up to 2,470ppm of melamine.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Public concerns have resulted in demand and egg prices falling throughout the country.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Prices at a large Beijing wholesale market dropped 10%, and prices fell by 10% the day after news of the contamination broke in Hong Kong.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wholesalers have refused to stock products without melamine inspection certificates.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The *Beijing Youth Daily* reported that farmers had been forced to slaughter tens of thousands of chickens.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The website upset Chinese authorities, who detained Zhao in November 2009 and arrested him in December 2009.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Chinese government said that producers violating the law "could have their licenses revoked and be handed over to law enforcement organs".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A senior Agriculture Ministry official said that of a quarter of a million feed-makers and animal farms inspected for melamine contamination, inspectors found more than 500 engaged in "illegal or questionable practices".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some 3,700 tonnes of feed with excessive melamine were seized.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Local government, for example Guangdong authorities, have increased random inspections at poultry farms.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They declared to "harshly crack down on the unlawful behaviour of illegally manufacturing, selling and using melamine".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 2 December 2009, China detained three employees of Shaanxi Jinqiao Dairy Company in northwest China suspected of selling 5.25 tons of melamine-laced powdered milk to Nanning Yueqian Food Additive Company, in Guangxi.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 30 December 2009, Xinhua reported continuing problems: powder and flavouring products sold by another company involved in the original scandal–the Shanghai Panda Dairy Company–were found to contain illegal levels of melamine; the dairy was closed and three of its executives arrested.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 25 January 2010, it was reported that three food companies from Hebei, Liaoning and Shandong provinces had produced melamine tainted products in March and April 2009 and that the three companies were banned from selling products in Guizhou.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 10 February 2010 China's state council announced a food safety commission, consisting of three vice premiers and a dozen minister-level officials, to address the nation's food regulatory problems.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The group aims to improve government coordination and enforcement and to solve systemic food safety problems.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] In July 2010, Xinhua reported that authorities had seized 64 tonnes of dairy product contaminated with melamine from Dongyuan Dairy Factory, in Minhe County, in Qinghai, after authorities in Gansu discovered the contaminated powdered milk.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Approximately 38 tonnes of raw materials had been purchased from Hebei, raising the possibility that traders had bought tainted milk that was supposed to have been destroyed after the 2008 scandal.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Police have detained the owner and production director of the factory.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Powdered milk produced in the plant was mainly sold in Zhejiang and Jiangsu, with only a small amount sold in Qinghai.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Also, in Jilin, authorities were testing samples of suspect powdered milk produced in Heilongjiang.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] At the end of June 2010, Beijing lowered the minimum protein level for raw milk, from 2.955 to 2.8%, to discourage dairy farmers from attempting to falsify the passing of protein tests.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wu Heping, secretary general of the Heilongjiang Dairy Industry Association noted that between 75% and 90% of raw milk in some provinces had failed to reach the old protein level standard (in place since 1986) in 2007 and 2008.
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] He said that the new standard reflected "the reality of the domestic dairy farm industry".
[src:2008-chinese-milk-scandal/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] However, Guangzhou dairy industry association president Wang Dingmian stated that this alone would not remove the incentive for adulteration, because milk price still depends on protein content.
